distinct() Method in Java Stream API

distinct() is an intermediate operation that removes duplicate elements from a stream.

👉 It keeps only unique elements.

Method Signature
Stream<T> distinct()
Return Value

Returns a new Stream containing only unique elements.

Basic Example
List<Integer> numbers =
        List.of(1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 4);

numbers.stream()
       .distinct()
       .forEach(System.out::println);

Output:

1
2
3
4
How distinct() Works

Given:

1
2
2
3
3
4
4
4

After calling distinct():

1
2
3
4

Every duplicate is removed.

Example with Strings
List<String> fruits =
        List.of(
            "Apple",
            "Banana",
            "Apple",
            "Orange",
            "Banana"
        );

fruits.stream()
      .distinct()
      .forEach(System.out::println);

Output:

Apple
Banana
Orange
How Does distinct() Know an Element Is a Duplicate?

distinct() uses:

equals()
hashCode()

This is the same mechanism used by HashSet.

For custom objects, you must correctly override both methods.

Example:

class Person {

    private String name;

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object obj) {
        // compare objects
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        // generate hash code
    }
}

Without equals() and hashCode(), distinct() may not remove duplicates correctly.

Example with Custom Objects
people.stream()
      .distinct()
      .forEach(System.out::println);

If equals() and hashCode() are implemented correctly, duplicate Person objects will be removed.

Using distinct() with Other Stream Operations
numbers.stream()
       .distinct()
       .sorted()
       .forEach(System.out::println);

Execution:

Original
↓
distinct()
↓
sorted()
↓
forEach()
distinct() Is an Intermediate Operation

This does nothing yet:

numbers.stream()
       .distinct();

Execution starts only after a terminal operation:

numbers.stream()
       .distinct()
       .forEach(System.out::println);
Original Collection Is Not Modified
List<Integer> numbers =
        List.of(1, 2, 2, 3);
numbers.stream()
       .distinct()
       .toList();

Original list:

[1, 2, 2, 3]

remains unchanged.

Time Complexity

On average:

O(n)

because each element is checked only once.

Common Use Cases
